One novel approach to predict the cirrhosis outcomes is to use a decision tree model. We can create a set of rules based on the input parameters and their relationship to the different outcomes. By evaluating the input values against these rules, we can determine the probabilities for each outcome and return the results.

```javascript
function PredictCirrhosisOutcomes(N_Days, Drug, Age, Sex, Ascites, Hepatomegaly, Spiders, Edema, Bilirubin, Cholesterol, Albumin, Copper, Alk_Phos, SGOT, Tryglicerides, Platelets, Prothrombin, Stage) {
  var Status_C = 0.0; // Placeholder values
  var Status_CL = 0.0; // Placeholder values
  var Status_D = 0.0; // Placeholder values

  // Decision tree rules based on input parameters
  if (N_Days < 1000 && (Drug === "D-penicillamine" || Age < 10000)) {
    Status_C = 0.8;
  } else if (Ascites === "Y" && (Bilirubin > 2.0 || Stage >= 3.0)) {
    Status_D = 0.9;
  } else {
    Status_CL = 0.7;
  }

  return {
    Status_C: Status_C,
    Status_CL: Status_CL,
    Status_D: Status_D
  };
}
```

